		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">William Hazlitt</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">Not to be confused with <a href="/wiki/William_Carew_Hazlitt" title="William Carew Hazlitt">William Carew Hazlitt</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:William_Hazlitt_self-portrait_(1802).jpg" class="image" title="William Hazlitt, self-portrait made circa 1802"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/87/William_Hazlitt_self-portrait_%281802%29.jpg" width="200" height="261" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:William_Hazlitt_self-portrait_(1802).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
William Hazlitt, self-portrait made circa 1802</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>William Hazlitt</b> (<span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1778-04-10"><a href="/wiki/April_10" title="April 10">10 April</a> <a href="/wiki/1778" title="1778">1778</a></span> – <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1830-09-18"><a href="/wiki/September_18" title="September 18">18 September</a> <a href="/wiki/1830" title="1830">1830</a></span>) was an English <a href="/wiki/Writer" title="Writer">writer</a> remembered for his humanistic <a href="/wiki/Essay" title="Essay">essays</a> and <a href="/wiki/Literary_criticism" title="Literary criticism">literary criticism</a>. Hazlitt was a prominent English literary critic, grammarian and philosopher. He is considered one of the greatest critics and <a href="/wiki/Essayist" title="Essayist" class="mw-redirect">essayists</a> in English,<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> placed in the same company as <a href="/wiki/Samuel_Johnson" title="Samuel Johnson">Samuel Johnson</a> and <a href="/wiki/George_Orwell" title="George Orwell">George Orwell</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> but his work is currently little-read.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
